{"title_page": "Masaru Emoto", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Masaru Emoto<br/>\u6c5f\u672c\u52dd\n| image         = Masaru_Emoto.jpg\n| image_size    =\n| caption       =\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1943|07|22}}\n| birth_place   = [[Yokohama]], Japan\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|2014|10|17|1943|1|24|mf=y}}\n| death_place   = Japan\n| education      = Yokohama Municipal University\n| occupation     =\n| spouse         = Kazuko Emoto\n| parents        = \n| children       =\n}}\n{{nihongo|'''Masaru Emoto'''|\u6c5f\u672c \u52dd|''Emoto Masaru''|July 22, 1943 \u2013 October 17, 2014}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Dr. Masaru Emoto, 1943\u20132014|url=http://www.beyondword.com/blog/dr.-masaru-emoto-1943-2014|publisher=Beyond Words|accessdate=20 October 2014|date=17 October 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923090023/http://www.beyondword.com/blog/dr.-masaru-emoto-1943-2014|archivedate=23 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Masaru Emoto|url=http://www.koha-verlag.de/autoren/info/autor/masaru-emoto.html|publisher=Koha Verlag|accessdate=20 October 2014|language=German}}</ref> was a [[Japan]]ese [[author]] and scientist who said that human consciousness has an effect on the [[Properties of water|molecular structure of water]]. Emoto's conjecture evolved over the years, and his early work revolved around [[pseudoscience|scientific]] hypotheses that water could react to positive thoughts and words and that polluted water could be cleaned through [[prayer]] and positive visualization.<ref name= \"Neimark2005\">{{cite news |last= Neimark |first= Jill |authorlink= Jill Neimark |date= September\u2013October 2005 |title= Messages from water? |magazine= Spirituality & Health}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Snowflake Myths and Nonsense|url=http://www.its.caltech.edu/~atomic/snowcrystals/myths/myths.html|author=Kenneth G. Libbrecht |publisher=[[California Institute of Technology]] |accessdate=21 July 2012|author-link=Kenneth G. Libbrecht}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The minds boggle|newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=16 May 2005|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/science/2005/may/16/g2.science}}</ref><ref name=\"MasaruWonderful\">{{cite web|title=Masaru Emoto's Wonderful World of Water|author=Harriet Hall |website = [[Skeptical Inquirer]] |date=November 2007|url=http://www.redorbit.com/news/science/1144934/masaru_emotos_wonderful_world_of_water|author-link=Harriet Hall }}</ref>\n\nSince 1999, Emoto published several volumes of a work entitled ''Messages from Water'', which contain photographs of [[Ice|ice crystals]] and their accompanying experiments.\n\n<br />\n\n==Biography==\nEmoto was born in [[Yokohama]], [[Japan]], and graduated from [[Yokohama City University|Yokohama Municipal University]] after taking courses in [[International Relations]]. In the mid-1990s, he began studying water in more detail.<ref>{{cite web |title= Authors: Dr. Masaru Emoto |publisher= [[Beyond Words Publishing]] |url= http://www.beyondword.com/authors/Dr._Masaru_Emoto |accessdate= 2013-07-01 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130602043746/http://www.beyondword.com/authors/Dr._Masaru_Emoto |archivedate= 2013-06-02 }}{{Unreliable source?|date=April 2010}}</ref>\n\nEmoto was President Emeritus of the International Water For Life Foundation, a [[non-profit organization]] based in [[Oklahoma City, Oklahoma|Oklahoma City]] in the [[United States]].<ref name= \"Reville2011\">{{cite news |last= Reville |first= William |date= February 17, 2011 |title= The pseudoscience of creating beautiful (or ugly) water |newspaper= [[The Irish Times]] |location= Dublin |page= 14 |id= {{ProQuest|851900025}} }}</ref> In 1992, Emoto became a Doctor of Alternative Medicine at the Open International University for Alternative Medicine<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://oiucm.net/|title=OIUCMED {{!}} The Open International University for Complementary Medicines|website=OIUCMED {{!}} The Open International University for Complementary Medicines|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-04}}</ref> in India,<ref name= \"Neimark2005\"/><ref>{{cite web |url= http://is-masaru-emoto-for-real.com/ |first= Kristopher |last= Setchfield |title= Are Dr. Masaru Emoto's Fantastic Claims Actually Real? |work= is-masaru-emoto-for-real.com |access-date= 2014-01-26 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190504023842/http://is-masaru-emoto-for-real.com/ |archive-date= 2019-05-04 |url-status= dead }}</ref><ref name= \"Kiesling2009\">{{cite news |last= Kiesling |first= Stephen |date= May\u2013June 2009 |title= Latest message from water: Is Dr. Emoto a spiritual Madoff? |magazine= Spirituality & Health |url= http://spirituality-health.com/articles/latest-message-water-dr-emoto-spiritual-madoff |accessdate= 2014-08-21|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826160731/http://spirituality-health.com/articles/latest-message-water-dr-emoto-spiritual-madoff|archivedate=2014-08-26}}</ref><ref name= \"Gordon2004\">{{cite news |last= Gordon |first= Sari |date= September\u2013October 2004 |title= He talks to water ...and the water talks back. Meet Dr. Emoto |magazine= [[Utne Reader]] |issue= 125 |page= 73 |id= {{ProQuest|217433470}} }}</ref> a [[diploma mill]] which targeted [[Quackery | quacks]] to sell its degrees<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/trichy/fake-university-vc-targeted-only-quacks-to-issue-degrees/articleshow/67495657.cms|title=Fake university 'VC' targeted only quacks to issue degrees - Times of India|website=The Times of India|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref> and was later shut down.<ref name=\"skeptoid\">{{Skeptoid | id=4433 | number= 433| title= The Water Woo of Masaru Emoto| date=September 23, 2014 | accessdate= 4 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/fake-varsity-sealed-after-operating-for-12-years/article25963820.ece|title=Fake varsity sealed after operating for 12 years|last=Jaisankar|first=C.|date=2019-01-11|work=The Hindu|access-date=2019-03-11|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\n==Ideas==\n\nEmoto said that water was a \"blueprint for our reality\" and that emotional \"energies\" and \"vibrations\" could change the physical structure of water.<ref name= \"Gray2003\">{{cite news |last= Gray |first= Donna |date= July 26, 2003 |title= Message in the water |newspaper= [[Calgary Herald]] |page= S8 |id= {{ProQuest|245079696}} }}</ref> Emoto's water crystal experiments consisted of exposing water in glasses to different words, pictures, or music and then freezing and examining the [[aesthetic]] properties of the resulting crystals with microscopic photography.<ref name= \"Reville2011\"/><ref>{{cite web |title= How to Take a Water Crystal Photograph |url= http://www.masaru-emoto.net/english/ediary200609.html#0915 |website= masaru-emoto.net |accessdate= 2011-10-10 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20111018110026/http://www.masaru-emoto.net/english/ediary200609.html |archivedate= 2011-10-18}}{{Failed verification|date=February 2014}}</ref> Emoto made the claim that water exposed to positive speech and thoughts would result in visually \"pleasing\" crystals being formed when that water was frozen and that negative intention would yield \"ugly\" frozen crystal formations.<ref>{{cite journal | url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S1550830706003272 | author=Dean Radin and Gail Hayssen and Masaru Emoto and Takashige Kizu | title=Double-Blind Test of the Effects of Distant Intention  on Water Crystal Formation | journal=[[Explore: The Journal of Science & Healing]] | volume=2 | number=5 | pages=408&ndash;411 | date=Sep 2006 }}</ref><ref name= \"Reville2011\"/>\n\nEmoto held that different water sources would produce different crystalline structures when frozen. For example, he held that a water sample from a mountain stream when frozen would show structures of beautifully shaped geometric design, but those structures would be distorted and randomly formed if the sample were taken from a polluted water source. Emoto held that these changes could be eliminated by exposing water to [[ultraviolet|ultraviolet light]] or certain [[Electromagnetic radiation|electromagnetic waves]].<ref name= \"Gray2003\"/>\n\nIn 2008, Emoto published his findings in the ''[[Journal of Scientific Exploration]]'', a [[scientific journal]] of the [[Society for Scientific Exploration]] that has been criticized for catering to [[fringe science]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1064461,00.html|title=Science on the Fringe|date=2005-05-24|publisher=[[Time magazine]]|author=Michael D. Lemonick/Gainesville|accessdate=2008-06-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Volume 22, Number 4 (2008) {{!}} Society for Scientific Exploration|url = http://www.scientificexploration.org/journal/volume-22-number-4-2008|website = www.scientificexploration.org|access-date = 2016-02-09}}</ref> The work was conducted and authored by Masaru Emoto and Takashige Kizu of Emoto\u2019s own IHM General Institute, along with [[Dean Radin]] and Nancy Lund of the [[Institute of Noetic Sciences]], which is on [[Stephen_Barrett#Consumer_information|Stephen Barrett's]] [[Quackwatch]] list of questionable organizations.<ref>{{cite web|last=Barrett|first=Stephen|title=Questionable Organizations: An Overview|url=http://www.quackwatch.org/04ConsumerEducation/nonrecorg.html|publisher=[[Quackwatch]]|accessdate=14 October 2013}}</ref>\nIn the experiment, more than 1,900 of Emoto's followers focused feelings of gratitude toward water stored in bottles, which was then frozen and its crystalline formations inspected.<ref name= \"Kiesling2009\"/> The gratitude-focused crystals were rated slightly more \"beautiful\" than one set of control crystals and slightly less \"beautiful\" than the other controls. An objective comparison of the samples did not reveal any significant differences.<ref name= \"Kiesling2009\"/>\n\n==Scientific criticism==\nCommentators have criticized Emoto for insufficient [[experimental control]]s and for not sharing enough details of his approach with the scientific community.<ref name= \"Reville2011\"/><ref>{{cite news |last= Koh |first= Lay Chin |date= January 28, 2009 |title= A 'hado' will never replace a home full of life |newspaper= [[New Straits Times]] |location= Kuala Lumpur, MY |page= 17 |id= {{ProQuest|272168250}} }}</ref> [[William A. Tiller]], another researcher featured in the documentary ''[[What The Bleep Do We Know?]]'', states that Emoto's experiments fall short of proof since they do not control for other factors in the [[supercooling]] of water.<ref>{{cite journal |title= What the Bleep do we Know!?: A Personal Narrative |last= Tiller |first= William |authorlink= William A. Tiller |journal= Vision in Action |volume= 2 |issue= 3\u20134 |year= 2004 |url= http://www.via-visioninaction.org/via-li/journals/What_the_Bleep_Perspectives_Vol2_No3-4.pdf}}</ref> In addition, Emoto has been criticized for designing his experiments in ways that leave them prone to manipulation or human error influencing the findings.<ref name= \"Reville2011\"/><ref name= \"Kiesling2009\"/><!-- remark out unclear ref <ref>For example, see Radin et al., 2006, page 408.{{Full|date=February 2014}}</ref> --><ref>{{cite journal |first= Robert |last= Matthews |authorlink= Robert Matthews (scientist) |title= Water: The quantum elixir |journal= [[New Scientist]] |issue= 2546 |date= April 8, 2006 |url= https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg19025461.200-water-the-quantum-elixir.html |url-access=subscription }}</ref> [[Biochemist]] and Director of Microscopy at [[University College Cork]] William Reville wrote, \"It is very unlikely that there is any reality behind Emoto's claims.\"<ref name= \"Reville2011\"/> Reville noted the lack of scientific publication and pointed out that anyone who could demonstrate such a phenomenon would become immediately famous and probably wealthy.<ref name= \"Reville2011\"/>\n\nWriting about Emoto's ideas in the ''[[Skeptical Inquirer]]'', physician [[Harriet A. Hall]] concluded that it was \"hard to see how anyone could mistake it for science\".<ref name=\"MasaruWonderful\"/> Commenting on Emoto's ideas about clearing water polluted by algae, biologist [[Tyler Volk]] stated, \"What he is saying has nothing to do with science as I know it.\"<ref name= \"Neimark2005\"/>  Stephen Kiesling wrote in ''Spirituality & Health Magazine'', \"Perhaps Emoto is an evangelist who values the message of his images more than the particulars of science; nevertheless, this spiritual teacher might focus his future practice less on gratitude and more on honesty.\"<ref name= \"Kiesling2009\"/>\n\nEmoto was personally invited to take the [[One Million Dollar Paranormal Challenge]] by [[James Randi]] in 2003 and would have received US$1,000,000 if he had been able to reproduce the experiment under test conditions agreed to by both parties. He did not participate.<ref name=\"Mason2010\">{{cite book |last= Mason |first= Phil |authorlink= Phil Mason |title= Quantum Glory: The Science of Heaven Invading Earth |year= 2010 |location= Maricopa, AZ |publisher= XP Publishing |isbn= 9781936101597|page= [https://books.google.com/books?id=EbSuDtaOH_cC&pg=PA150 150]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last= Randi |first= James |authorlink= James Randi |date= May 23, 2003 |title= Chiropractic Crackup, Talking to Water, Sylvia Emerges!, Bidlack's Lumps, An MS Miracle, and a Korean Magic Stone... |url= http://www.randi.org/jr/052303.html |publisher= [[James Randi Educational Foundation]] |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20030602141607/http://www.randi.org/jr/052303.html |archivedate= 2003-06-02 |work= Swift |type= online newsletter}}</ref>\n\n==Literary reception==\n\nEmoto's book ''The Hidden Messages in Water'' was a [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''New York Times'' best seller]].<ref>{{cite news |last= Previch |first= Chad |date= January 21, 2006 |title= Want rain? It's all in the brain, expert says |newspaper= [[The Oklahoman]] |agency= [[Knight Ridder]] |id= {{ProQuest|463050722}} }}</ref><ref name= \"Garner2005\"/> Commenting on the book making the list, literary critic [[Dwight Garner (critic)|Dwight Garner]] wrote in ''[[The New York Times Book Review]]'' that it was one of those \"head-scratchers\" that made him question the sanity of the reading public, describing the book as \"spectacularly eccentric.\"<ref name= \"Garner2005\">{{cite news |last= Garner |first= Dwight |authorlink= Dwight Garner (critic) |date= March 13, 2005 |title= TBR: Inside the list |newspaper= [[The New York Times Book Review]] |page= 30 |id= {{ProQuest|217307067}} }}</ref>  ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' described Emoto's later work, ''The Shape of Love'', as \"mostly incoherent and unsatisfying\".<ref>{{cite news |date= February 12, 2007 |title= ''The Shape of Love: Discovering Who We Are, Where We Came From, and Where We're Going'' |type= book review |magazine= [[Publishers Weekly]] |volume= 254 |issue= 7 |page= 79}}</ref>\n\nEmoto's ideas appeared in the movies ''[[Kamen Rider: The First]]'' and ''[[What the Bleep Do We Know!?]]''.<ref name= \"Guardian2005\">{{cite news |title= The minds boggle |newspaper= [[The Guardian]] |date= May 15, 2005 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2005/may/16/g2.science}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= Olmsted |first= John |date= October 1, 2004 |title= Ramtha's school of quantum flapdoodle |url= http://www.skeptic.com/eskeptic/04-10-01/ |magazine= eSkeptic |issn= 1556-5696 |publisher= [[The Skeptics Society|Skeptics Society]] |type= movie review |accessdate= 2014-08-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last= Poppy |first= Carrie |authorlink= Oh No, Ross and Carrie! |work= Poppycock |publisher= [[Committee for Skeptical Inquiry]] |type= blog |date= March 11, 2014 |title= A grain of truth: Recreating Dr. Emoto's rice experiment |url= https://skepticalinquirer.org/exclusive/a-grain-of-truth-recreating-dr-_emotos-rice-experiment |accessdate= 2014-08-21}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n\n===Books===\n* {{cite book |title= \u6c34\u304b\u3089\u306e\u4f1d\u8a00: \u4e16\u754c\u521d!! \u6c34\u306e\u7d50\u6676\u5199\u771f\u96c6 (Mizu kara no dengon: sekaihatsu!! mizu no kessh\u014d shashinsh\u016b) |language= JA |trans-title=Messages from Water |volume= 1 |year= 1999 |location= Tokyo |publisher= Hado |isbn= 9784939098000 |last= Emoto |first= Masaru |authormask=0}} \n** English edition: {{cite book |last= Emoto |first= Masaru |authormask= 0 |year= 2000 |title= The Message from Water: The Message from Water is Telling Us to Take a Look at Ourselves |volume= 1 |publisher= Hado |isbn= 9784939098000}}\n* {{cite book |title= \u6c34\u304b\u3089\u306e\u4f1d\u8a00\uff1a \u4e16\u754c\u521d\uff01\uff01\u6c34\u306e\u6c37\u7d50\u7d50\u6676\u5199\u771f\u96c6\u4eca\u65e5\u3082\u6c34\u306b\u3042\u308a\u304c\u3068\u3046 (Mizu kara no dengon: sekaihatsu!! mizu no kessh\u014d shashinsh\u016b) |language= JA |trans-title=The Messages from Water |location= Tokyo |publisher= Hado |year= 2001 |last= Emoto |first= Masaru |authormask= 0 |volume= 2 |isbn= 9784939098048}}\n** English edition: {{cite book |last= Emoto |first= Masaru |authormask= 0 |title= The Message from Water |volume= 2 |publisher= Hado |year= 2001 |isbn= 9784939098048}}\n* {{cite book |last= Emoto |first= Masaru |authormask= 0 |title= \u6c34\u304c\u4f1d\u3048\u308b\u611b\u306e\u304b\u305f\u3061 (Mizu ga tsutaeru ai no katachi) |language= JA |location= Tokyo |publisher= [[Tokuma Shoten]] |year= 2003 |isbn= 9784198617509}}\n** English edition: {{cite book |last= Emoto |first= Masaru |authormask= 0 |title= The Shape of Love: Discovering Who We Are, Where We Came From, and Where We are Going |location= New York |publisher= [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]] |year= 2007 |isbn= 9780385518376}}\n* {{cite book |last= Emoto |first= Masaru |authormask= 0 |title= Love Thyself: The Message from Water III |year= 2004 |location= Carlsbad, CA |publisher= [[Hay House]] |isbn= 9781401908997}} \n* {{cite book |last= Emoto |first= Masaru |authormask= 0 |title= \u6c34\u53ef\u4ee5\u6539\u8b8a\u6211\u751f\u547d : \"\u611b\u548c\u611f\u8b1d\"\u7684\u5fc3\u60c5\u53ef\u4ee5\u5275\u9020\u7a4d\u6975\u7684\u80fd\u91cf (Shui ke yi gai bian wo sheng ming : \"Ai he gan xie\" de xin qing ke yi chuan zao ji ji de neng liang) |language= ZH |publisher= Taibei Xian Xindian Shi |year= 2006 |isbn= 9789576864971}}\n** English edition: {{cite book |last= Emoto |first= Masaru |authormask= 0 |title= The Miracle of Water |location= New York; Hillsboro, OR |publisher= [[Simon & Schuster#Adult publishing|Atria]]: [[Beyond Words Publishing|Beyond Words]] |year= 2007 |isbn= 9781582701622 |url-access= registration |url= https://archive.org/details/miracleofwater00emot }}\n* {{cite book |last= Emoto |first= Masaru |authormask= 0 |title= Water Crystal Healing: Music & Images to Restore Your Well Being |year= 2006 |location= New York; Hillsboro, OR |publisher= [[Simon & Schuster#Adult publishing|Atria]]: [[Beyond Words Publishing|Beyond Words]] |isbn= 9781582701561}}\n*''[[The True Power of Water (Book)]]: Healing and Discovering Ourselves''; [[Beyond Words Publishing|Beyond Words Pub]]., 2005. {{ISBN|9781582701288}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/The_True_Power_of_Water.html?id=Fr4zqDfsRRQC&source=kp_book_description&redir_esc=y|title=The True Power of Water: Healing and Discovering Ourselves|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Water memory]]\n*[[Polywater]]\n*[[Water (2006 film)|''Water'' (2006 film)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite news |last= Greenberg |first= Gary |date= February 6, 2006 |title= There's no evidence water can understand human speech |url= http://www.mauinews.com/page/content.detail/id/16702.html |newspaper= [[The Maui News]] |url-access=subscription }}\n*{{cite web |author= Orac (David Gorski) |authorlink= David Gorski |date= October 6, 2006 |title= Your Friday Dose of Woo: H2Ooooooommmm |url= http://scienceblogs.com/insolence/2006/10/06/your-friday-dose-of-woo-h2ooooooommmm-1/ |work= ScienceBlogs |type= blog}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.masaru-emoto.net/}}\n* {{IMDb name|2168634|Masaru Emoto}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Emoto, Masaru}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Yokohama]]\n[[Category:Japanese writers]]\n[[Category:Japanese activists]]\n[[Category:New Age writers]]\n[[Category:Water physics controversies]]\n[[Category:Pseudoscience]]\n[[Category:Parapsychologists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Masaru Emoto<br/>\u6c5f\u672c\u52dd\n| image         = Masaru_Emoto.jpg\n| image_size    =\n| caption       =\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1943|07|22}}\n| birth_place   = [[Yokohama]], Japan\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|2014|10|17|1943|1|24|mf=y}}\n| death_place   = Japan\n| education      = Yokohama Municipal University\n| occupation     =\n| spouse         = Kazuko Emoto\n| parents        = \n| children       =\n}}\n{{nihongo|'''Masaru Emoto'''|\u6c5f\u672c \u52dd|''Emoto Masaru''|July 22, 1943 \u2013 October 17, 2014}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Dr. Masaru Emoto, 1943\u20132014|url=http://www.beyondword.com/blog/dr.-masaru-emoto-1943-2014|publisher=Beyond Words|accessdate=20 October 2014|date=17 October 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923090023/http://www.beyondword.com/blog/dr.-masaru-emoto-1943-2014|archivedate=23 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Masaru Emoto|url=http://www.koha-verlag.de/autoren/info/autor/masaru-emoto.html|publisher=Koha Verlag|accessdate=20 October 2014|language=German}}</ref> was a [[Japan]]ese [[author]] and pseudo-scientist who said that human consciousness has an effect on the [[Properties of water|molecular structure of water]]. Emoto's conjecture evolved over the years, and his early work revolved around [[pseudoscience|pseudo-scientific]] hypotheses that water could react to positive thoughts and words and that polluted water could be cleaned through [[prayer]] and positive visualization.<ref name= \"Neimark2005\">{{cite news |last= Neimark |first= Jill |authorlink= Jill Neimark |date= September\u2013October 2005 |title= Messages from water? |magazine= Spirituality & Health}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Snowflake Myths and Nonsense|url=http://www.its.caltech.edu/~atomic/snowcrystals/myths/myths.html|author=Kenneth G. Libbrecht |publisher=[[California Institute of Technology]] |accessdate=21 July 2012|author-link=Kenneth G. Libbrecht}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The minds boggle|newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=16 May 2005|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/science/2005/may/16/g2.science}}</ref><ref name=\"MasaruWonderful\">{{cite web|title=Masaru Emoto's Wonderful World of Water|author=Harriet Hall |website = [[Skeptical Inquirer]] |date=November 2007|url=http://www.redorbit.com/news/science/1144934/masaru_emotos_wonderful_world_of_water|author-link=Harriet Hall }}</ref>\n\nSince 1999, Emoto published several volumes of a work entitled ''Messages from Water'', which contain photographs of [[Ice|ice crystals]] and their accompanying experiments.\n\n==Biography==\nEmoto was born in [[Yokohama]], [[Japan]], and graduated from [[Yokohama City University|Yokohama Municipal University]] after taking courses in [[International Relations]]. In the mid-1990s, he began studying water in more detail.<ref>{{cite web |title= Authors: Dr. Masaru Emoto |publisher= [[Beyond Words Publishing]] |url= http://www.beyondword.com/authors/Dr._Masaru_Emoto |accessdate= 2013-07-01 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130602043746/http://www.beyondword.com/authors/Dr._Masaru_Emoto |archivedate= 2013-06-02 }}{{Unreliable source?|date=April 2010}}</ref>\n\nEmoto was President Emeritus of the International Water For Life Foundation, a [[non-profit organization]] based in [[Oklahoma City, Oklahoma|Oklahoma City]] in the [[United States]].<ref name= \"Reville2011\">{{cite news |last= Reville |first= William |date= February 17, 2011 |title= The pseudoscience of creating beautiful (or ugly) water |newspaper= [[The Irish Times]] |location= Dublin |page= 14 |id= {{ProQuest|851900025}} }}</ref> In 1992, Emoto became a Doctor of Alternative Medicine at the Open International University for Alternative Medicine<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://oiucm.net/|title=OIUCMED {{!}} The Open International University for Complementary Medicines|website=OIUCMED {{!}} The Open International University for Complementary Medicines|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-04}}</ref> in India,<ref name= \"Neimark2005\"/><ref>{{cite web |url= http://is-masaru-emoto-for-real.com/ |first= Kristopher |last= Setchfield |title= Are Dr. Masaru Emoto's Fantastic Claims Actually Real? |work= is-masaru-emoto-for-real.com |access-date= 2014-01-26 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190504023842/http://is-masaru-emoto-for-real.com/ |archive-date= 2019-05-04 |url-status= dead }}</ref><ref name= \"Kiesling2009\">{{cite news |last= Kiesling |first= Stephen |date= May\u2013June 2009 |title= Latest message from water: Is Dr. Emoto a spiritual Madoff? |magazine= Spirituality & Health |url= http://spirituality-health.com/articles/latest-message-water-dr-emoto-spiritual-madoff |accessdate= 2014-08-21|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826160731/http://spirituality-health.com/articles/latest-message-water-dr-emoto-spiritual-madoff|archivedate=2014-08-26}}</ref><ref name= \"Gordon2004\">{{cite news |last= Gordon |first= Sari |date= September\u2013October 2004 |title= He talks to water ...and the water talks back. Meet Dr. Emoto |magazine= [[Utne Reader]] |issue= 125 |page= 73 |id= {{ProQuest|217433470}} }}</ref> a [[diploma mill]] which targeted [[Quackery | quacks]] to sell its degrees<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/trichy/fake-university-vc-targeted-only-quacks-to-issue-degrees/articleshow/67495657.cms|title=Fake university 'VC' targeted only quacks to issue degrees - Times of India|website=The Times of India|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref> and was later shut down.<ref name=\"skeptoid\">{{Skeptoid | id=4433 | number= 433| title= The Water Woo of Masaru Emoto| date=September 23, 2014 | accessdate= 4 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/fake-varsity-sealed-after-operating-for-12-years/article25963820.ece|title=Fake varsity sealed after operating for 12 years|last=Jaisankar|first=C.|date=2019-01-11|work=The Hindu|access-date=2019-03-11|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\n==Ideas==\n\nEmoto said that water was a \"blueprint for our reality\" and that emotional \"energies\" and \"vibrations\" could change the physical structure of water.<ref name= \"Gray2003\">{{cite news |last= Gray |first= Donna |date= July 26, 2003 |title= Message in the water |newspaper= [[Calgary Herald]] |page= S8 |id= {{ProQuest|245079696}} }}</ref> Emoto's water crystal experiments consisted of exposing water in glasses to different words, pictures, or music and then freezing and examining the [[aesthetic]] properties of the resulting crystals with microscopic photography.<ref name= \"Reville2011\"/><ref>{{cite web |title= How to Take a Water Crystal Photograph |url= http://www.masaru-emoto.net/english/ediary200609.html#0915 |website= masaru-emoto.net |accessdate= 2011-10-10 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20111018110026/http://www.masaru-emoto.net/english/ediary200609.html |archivedate= 2011-10-18}}{{Failed verification|date=February 2014}}</ref> Emoto made the claim that water exposed to positive speech and thoughts would result in visually \"pleasing\" crystals being formed when that water was frozen and that negative intention would yield \"ugly\" frozen crystal formations.<ref>{{cite journal | url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S1550830706003272 | author=Dean Radin and Gail Hayssen and Masaru Emoto and Takashige Kizu | title=Double-Blind Test of the Effects of Distant Intention  on Water Crystal Formation | journal=[[Explore: The Journal of Science & Healing]] | volume=2 | number=5 | pages=408&ndash;411 | date=Sep 2006 }}</ref><ref name= \"Reville2011\"/>\n\nEmoto held that different water sources would produce different crystalline structures when frozen. For example, he held that a water sample from a mountain stream when frozen would show structures of beautifully shaped geometric design, but those structures would be distorted and randomly formed if the sample were taken from a polluted water source. Emoto held that these changes could be eliminated by exposing water to [[ultraviolet|ultraviolet light]] or certain [[Electromagnetic radiation|electromagnetic waves]].<ref name= \"Gray2003\"/>\n\nIn 2008, Emoto published his findings in the ''[[Journal of Scientific Exploration]]'', a [[scientific journal]] of the [[Society for Scientific Exploration]] that has been criticized for catering to [[fringe science]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1064461,00.html|title=Science on the Fringe|date=2005-05-24|publisher=[[Time magazine]]|author=Michael D. Lemonick/Gainesville|accessdate=2008-06-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Volume 22, Number 4 (2008) {{!}} Society for Scientific Exploration|url = http://www.scientificexploration.org/journal/volume-22-number-4-2008|website = www.scientificexploration.org|access-date = 2016-02-09}}</ref> The work was conducted and authored by Masaru Emoto and Takashige Kizu of Emoto\u2019s own IHM General Institute, along with [[Dean Radin]] and Nancy Lund of the [[Institute of Noetic Sciences]], which is on [[Stephen_Barrett#Consumer_information|Stephen Barrett's]] [[Quackwatch]] list of questionable organizations.<ref>{{cite web|last=Barrett|first=Stephen|title=Questionable Organizations: An Overview|url=http://www.quackwatch.org/04ConsumerEducation/nonrecorg.html|publisher=[[Quackwatch]]|accessdate=14 October 2013}}</ref>\nIn the experiment, more than 1,900 of Emoto's followers focused feelings of gratitude toward water stored in bottles, which was then frozen and its crystalline formations inspected.<ref name= \"Kiesling2009\"/> The gratitude-focused crystals were rated slightly more \"beautiful\" than one set of control crystals and slightly less \"beautiful\" than the other controls. An objective comparison of the samples did not reveal any significant differences.<ref name= \"Kiesling2009\"/>\n\n==Scientific criticism==\nCommentators have criticized Emoto for insufficient [[experimental control]]s and for not sharing enough details of his approach with the scientific community.<ref name= \"Reville2011\"/><ref>{{cite news |last= Koh |first= Lay Chin |date= January 28, 2009 |title= A 'hado' will never replace a home full of life |newspaper= [[New Straits Times]] |location= Kuala Lumpur, MY |page= 17 |id= {{ProQuest|272168250}} }}</ref> [[William A. Tiller]], another researcher featured in the documentary ''[[What The Bleep Do We Know?]]'', states that Emoto's experiments fall short of proof since they do not control for other factors in the [[supercooling]] of water.<ref>{{cite journal |title= What the Bleep do we Know!?: A Personal Narrative |last= Tiller |first= William |authorlink= William A. Tiller |journal= Vision in Action |volume= 2 |issue= 3\u20134 |year= 2004 |url= http://www.via-visioninaction.org/via-li/journals/What_the_Bleep_Perspectives_Vol2_No3-4.pdf}}</ref> In addition, Emoto has been criticized for designing his experiments in ways that leave them prone to manipulation or human error influencing the findings.<ref name= \"Reville2011\"/><ref name= \"Kiesling2009\"/><!-- remark out unclear ref <ref>For example, see Radin et al., 2006, page 408.{{Full|date=February 2014}}</ref> --><ref>{{cite journal |first= Robert |last= Matthews |authorlink= Robert Matthews (scientist) |title= Water: The quantum elixir |journal= [[New Scientist]] |issue= 2546 |date= April 8, 2006 |url= https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg19025461.200-water-the-quantum-elixir.html |url-access=subscription }}</ref> [[Biochemist]] and Director of Microscopy at [[University College Cork]] William Reville wrote, \"It is very unlikely that there is any reality behind Emoto's claims.\"<ref name= \"Reville2011\"/> Reville noted the lack of scientific publication and pointed out that anyone who could demonstrate such a phenomenon would become immediately famous and probably wealthy.<ref name= \"Reville2011\"/>\n\nWriting about Emoto's ideas in the ''[[Skeptical Inquirer]]'', physician [[Harriet A. Hall]] concluded that it was \"hard to see how anyone could mistake it for science\".<ref name=\"MasaruWonderful\"/> Commenting on Emoto's ideas about clearing water polluted by algae, biologist [[Tyler Volk]] stated, \"What he is saying has nothing to do with science as I know it.\"<ref name= \"Neimark2005\"/>  Stephen Kiesling wrote in ''Spirituality & Health Magazine'', \"Perhaps Emoto is an evangelist who values the message of his images more than the particulars of science; nevertheless, this spiritual teacher might focus his future practice less on gratitude and more on honesty.\"<ref name= \"Kiesling2009\"/>\n\nEmoto was personally invited to take the [[One Million Dollar Paranormal Challenge]] by [[James Randi]] in 2003 and would have received US$1,000,000 if he had been able to reproduce the experiment under test conditions agreed to by both parties. He did not participate.<ref name=\"Mason2010\">{{cite book |last= Mason |first= Phil |authorlink= Phil Mason |title= Quantum Glory: The Science of Heaven Invading Earth |year= 2010 |location= Maricopa, AZ |publisher= XP Publishing |isbn= 9781936101597|page= [https://books.google.com/books?id=EbSuDtaOH_cC&pg=PA150 150]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last= Randi |first= James |authorlink= James Randi |date= May 23, 2003 |title= Chiropractic Crackup, Talking to Water, Sylvia Emerges!, Bidlack's Lumps, An MS Miracle, and a Korean Magic Stone... |url= http://www.randi.org/jr/052303.html |publisher= [[James Randi Educational Foundation]] |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20030602141607/http://www.randi.org/jr/052303.html |archivedate= 2003-06-02 |work= Swift |type= online newsletter}}</ref>\n\n==Literary reception==\n\nEmoto's book ''The Hidden Messages in Water'' was a [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''New York Times'' best seller]].<ref>{{cite news |last= Previch |first= Chad |date= January 21, 2006 |title= Want rain? It's all in the brain, expert says |newspaper= [[The Oklahoman]] |agency= [[Knight Ridder]] |id= {{ProQuest|463050722}} }}</ref><ref name= \"Garner2005\"/> Commenting on the book making the list, literary critic [[Dwight Garner (critic)|Dwight Garner]] wrote in ''[[The New York Times Book Review]]'' that it was one of those \"head-scratchers\" that made him question the sanity of the reading public, describing the book as \"spectacularly eccentric.\"<ref name= \"Garner2005\">{{cite news |last= Garner |first= Dwight |authorlink= Dwight Garner (critic) |date= March 13, 2005 |title= TBR: Inside the list |newspaper= [[The New York Times Book Review]] |page= 30 |id= {{ProQuest|217307067}} }}</ref>  ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' described Emoto's later work, ''The Shape of Love'', as \"mostly incoherent and unsatisfying\".<ref>{{cite news |date= February 12, 2007 |title= ''The Shape of Love: Discovering Who We Are, Where We Came From, and Where We're Going'' |type= book review |magazine= [[Publishers Weekly]] |volume= 254 |issue= 7 |page= 79}}</ref>\n\nEmoto's ideas appeared in the movies ''[[Kamen Rider: The First]]'' and ''[[What the Bleep Do We Know!?]]''.<ref name= \"Guardian2005\">{{cite news |title= The minds boggle |newspaper= [[The Guardian]] |date= May 15, 2005 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2005/may/16/g2.science}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= Olmsted |first= John |date= October 1, 2004 |title= Ramtha's school of quantum flapdoodle |url= http://www.skeptic.com/eskeptic/04-10-01/ |magazine= eSkeptic |issn= 1556-5696 |publisher= [[The Skeptics Society|Skeptics Society]] |type= movie review |accessdate= 2014-08-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last= Poppy |first= Carrie |authorlink= Oh No, Ross and Carrie! |work= Poppycock |publisher= [[Committee for Skeptical Inquiry]] |type= blog |date= March 11, 2014 |title= A grain of truth: Recreating Dr. Emoto's rice experiment |url= https://skepticalinquirer.org/exclusive/a-grain-of-truth-recreating-dr-_emotos-rice-experiment |accessdate= 2014-08-21}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n\n===Books===\n* {{cite book |title= \u6c34\u304b\u3089\u306e\u4f1d\u8a00: \u4e16\u754c\u521d!! \u6c34\u306e\u7d50\u6676\u5199\u771f\u96c6 (Mizu kara no dengon: sekaihatsu!! mizu no kessh\u014d shashinsh\u016b) |language= JA |trans-title=Messages from Water |volume= 1 |year= 1999 |location= Tokyo |publisher= Hado |isbn= 9784939098000 |last= Emoto |first= Masaru |authormask=0}} \n** English edition: {{cite book |last= Emoto |first= Masaru |authormask= 0 |year= 2000 |title= The Message from Water: The Message from Water is Telling Us to Take a Look at Ourselves |volume= 1 |publisher= Hado |isbn= 9784939098000}}\n* {{cite book |title= \u6c34\u304b\u3089\u306e\u4f1d\u8a00\uff1a \u4e16\u754c\u521d\uff01\uff01\u6c34\u306e\u6c37\u7d50\u7d50\u6676\u5199\u771f\u96c6\u4eca\u65e5\u3082\u6c34\u306b\u3042\u308a\u304c\u3068\u3046 (Mizu kara no dengon: sekaihatsu!! mizu no kessh\u014d shashinsh\u016b) |language= JA |trans-title=The Messages from Water |location= Tokyo |publisher= Hado |year= 2001 |last= Emoto |first= Masaru |authormask= 0 |volume= 2 |isbn= 9784939098048}}\n** English edition: {{cite book |last= Emoto |first= Masaru |authormask= 0 |title= The Message from Water |volume= 2 |publisher= Hado |year= 2001 |isbn= 9784939098048}}\n* {{cite book |last= Emoto |first= Masaru |authormask= 0 |title= \u6c34\u304c\u4f1d\u3048\u308b\u611b\u306e\